            "id": "ce246f6a04d74c20a9345",
            "questionText": "Astronomers observe the emission spectrum of a distant star composed primarily of hydrogen. They identify a spectral line corresponding to the transition of an electron from the energy level $!$n = 3$!$ to $!$n = 2$!$. Using the Bohr model for hydrogen, calculate the wavelength ($!$\\lambda$!$) of the emitted photon during this transition. Recall that the energy levels are given by $!$E_n = -\\frac{13.6}{n^2} \\text{ eV}$!$ and the energy of a photon is $!$E = \\frac{hc}{\\lambda}$!$, where $!$h = 4.135 \\times 10^{-15} \\text{ eV s}$!$ and $!$c = 3 \\times 10^8 \\text{ m/s}$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "db1bf42f0c6247eabd4b8",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct formula to calculate the energy levels of a hydrogen atom. Choose the formula that properly relates the principal quantum number, n, to the energy of that level.",
