        {
            "id": "7b139666b23944dca3458",
            "questionText": "Astronomers observe the hydrogen spectral line at $!$\\lambda_0 = 656.3 \\text{ nm}$!$ (Balmer alpha) in a distant galaxy. However, due to the galaxy's motion, the observed wavelength is redshifted to $!$\\lambda = 690.0 \\text{ nm}$!$. Based on this observed redshift, determine the velocity ($!$v$!$) at which the galaxy is receding from Earth, assuming the redshift ($!$z$!$) is given by $!$z = (\\lambda - \\lambda_0)/\\lambda_0$!$ and for relatively small velocities ($!$v \\ll c$!$), the redshift is also approximated by $!$z \\approx v/c$!$, where $!$c = 3 \\times 10^8 \\text{ m/s}$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "4ef20b6abd4f4080b3de8",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the formula used to calculate the redshift $!$z$!$ from the given wavelengths. Which of the following options represents the correct expression?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "b1d7aa44-8d11-4c29-963d-f20ee78901d7"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$z = (\\lambda - \\lambda_0)/\\lambda_0$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$z = \\lambda/ (\\lambda - \\lambda_0)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$z = \\lambda_0 / (\\lambda - \\lambda_0)$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "2bb60d8c49f347e9adce6",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, use the redshift formula to compute its numerical value by substituting $!$\\lambda_0 = 656.3\\text{ nm}$!$ and $!$\\lambda = 690.0\\text{ nm}$!$. What is the resulting value of $!$z$!$?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.0513"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "b1d7aa44-8d11-4c29-963d-f20ee78901d7"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
